The truth seems to be, that when Catiline came back from Africa to sue for the consulship, his object was ⁴merely to pass a few democratic measures‚ for the relies of debtors for instance, as consul, and then to enrich himself and his friends in the provinces But as matters went, he was for long the tool in the hands of men of more ability and influence than him- self. And it was only at last, under the pressure of repeated disappointment, that the Conspiracy, with its violence, its military preparations‚ and incen- diarism, was formed.

It is not necessary here to recount the whole story of the Conspiracy as we have received it, nor is it desired to discuss the many disputed details, or to attempt to decidebetween the conflicting views of the charac- ter of the movement. But one error of long standing as to the date of the consular Comitia of 691 (63) has been so satisfactorily set right¹⁶ and the correction removes so many improbabilities in the history of the Conspiracy when it reached its acute stage, that a few lines may be usefully devoted to that question.
